---
import Base from '../../../layouts/Base.astro';
import Breadcrumbs from '../../../components/Breadcrumbs.astro';
import Cta from '../../../components/Cta.astro';
import { reviewSchema, faqSchema, breadcrumbSchema, articleSchema } from '../../../lib/schema';
import { REVEAL_PATH } from '../../../lib/site';

const path = '/reviews/numerologist-review/';
const title = 'Numerologist.com Review (2026): Is It Legit or Overhyped?';
const description = 'An honest Numerologist.com review — what the free reading actually contains, what the paid reports cost, where it shines, where it falls short, and who should skip it.';
const crumbs = [
  { name: 'Home', href: '/' },
  { name: 'Reviews', href: '/reviews/' },
  { name: 'Numerologist.com', href: path },
];
const faqs = [
  { q: 'Is Numerologist.com legit?', a: 'Yes — it is a real company that has operated for well over a decade and delivers the reports it sells. Legitimacy and value are different questions: the reports are software-generated from your birthdate and name, and the upsell sequence after purchase is aggressive.' },
  { q: 'How much does Numerologist.com cost?', a: 'The entry reading is inexpensive (typically under $20 at the time of writing), but the checkout and email flow present multiple upsells. Verify current pricing on their site — it changes with promotions.' },
  { q: 'Is the free reading actually free?', a: 'The free reading is real but brief — it functions as a preview designed to lead into the paid report. Expect to provide your email address.' },
];
const schema = [
  articleSchema({ title, description, path }),
  reviewSchema({
    itemName: 'Numerologist.com Personalized Numerology Report',
    itemUrl: 'https://www.numerologist.com',
    rating: 3.5,
    path,
    description:
      'A polished, long-running personalized numerology report service with strong production value, offset by software-generated depth and a heavy upsell sequence.',
  }),
  faqSchema(faqs),
  breadcrumbSchema(crumbs),
];
---

<Base title={title} description={description} schema={schema}>
  <div class="article">
    <Breadcrumbs crumbs={crumbs} />
    <header>
      <p class="eyebrow">Review · Updated July 2026</p>
      <h1>Numerologist.com Review: Is It Worth It in 2026?</h1>
    </header>

    <p class="notice">
      Disclosure: this page may contain affiliate links, including to Numerologist.com and to our own
      Frequency Code™ report. We may earn a commission at no cost to you. Our assessment draws on the
      publicly available checkout flow, the free reading, and the report structure Numerologist.com
      advertises and delivers.
    </p>

    <div class="verdict">
      <p class="eyebrow">The Verdict</p>
      <p><span class="score">3.5</span> / 5</p>
      <p>
        Numerologist.com is the biggest name in personalized numerology reports, and it earns part of
        that reputation: the entry price is low, delivery is instant, and the production quality is
        high. It loses points for depth — the reports are assembled by software from your birthdate
        and name — and for an upsell sequence that starts at checkout and continues in your inbox for
        weeks. Worth trying at the entry price if you are curious; skip the upsells until you have
        read the first report.
      </p>
    </div>

    <h2>What Numerologist.com Actually Is</h2>
    <p>
      Numerologist.com sells personalized numerology readings: you enter your name and date of birth,
      watch a video presentation, and receive a multi-page report covering your life path, expression
      number, soul urge, and forecast periods. The company has operated since the 2000s and built its
      audience primarily through advertising and one of the largest affiliate programs in the
      spirituality niche — which is why most "reviews" you will find online are written by people
      paid to say yes. This one is written by a competitor, which you should also weigh. We sell our
      own reading, we say so openly, and we have kept this review to things you can verify yourself.
    </p>

    <h2>What You Get</h2>
    <p>
      The funnel runs in two stages. The free reading asks for your name and date of birth, then
      returns a short preview — your life path number and a few lines on what it means — in exchange
      for an email address. It is enough to be useful, not enough to be the point; it exists to lead
      into the paid report. The paid tier expands the same inputs into a longer, multi-section
      breakdown covering life path, expression, and soul urge, plus forecast periods tied to the
      current year. Because the report is generated from your name and birthdate alone, the sections
      built directly from those numbers read as specific; the surrounding narrative connective tissue
      reads more generic, the same way most software-assembled reports do.
    </p>

    <h2>Where It Shines</h2>
    <p>
      The onboarding is genuinely well made: the free reading gives you real information before asking
      for money, the entry price is impulse-level, and delivery is immediate. For someone brand new to
      numerology, it is a low-risk introduction to the vocabulary — life path, expression, soul urge —
      that every deeper practice builds on.
    </p>

    <h2>Where It Falls Short</h2>
    <p>
      Three things. First, depth: the reports read like well-written templates keyed to your numbers,
      because that is what they are. Two people with the same birthdate receive the same reading.
      Second, the upsells: expect additional offers at checkout and a long email sequence afterward.
      Third, focus: Numerologist.com is a numerology product. If the thing that brought you here is a
      repeating number — 444 on clocks, 1111 on receipts — angel numbers are treated as an
      afterthought there, not the center.
    </p>

    <h2>Numerologist.com vs. the Frequency Code™</h2>
    <table>
      <thead><tr><th></th><th>Numerologist.com</th><th>Frequency Code™ (ours)</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>Core focus</td><td>Classical numerology chart</td><td>Angel numbers + the pattern beneath them</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Report</td><td>Multi-part numerology reading</td><td>26-page personalized Frequency Code report</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Free version</td><td>Free mini reading (email required)</td><td>Free angel number reveal, no email required</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Price</td><td>Low entry, multiple upsells</td><td>$27, single report</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Best for</td><td>Numerology-first beginners</td><td>People who keep seeing repeating numbers</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
    <p>
      We are not neutral here, so the honest framing is fit, not winner: if you want a classical
      numerology chart, theirs is a reasonable entry point. If a number keeps finding you and you want
      to know why, that is the exact question our report was built to answer.
    </p>

    <Cta
      heading="Try the question our report answers"
      line="Start free: reveal the number in your birthdate first, no email required."
      secondaryHref="/angel-numbers/calculator/"
      secondaryLabel="Free angel number calculator"
    />

    <section class="faq" aria-labelledby="faq-h">
      <h2 id="faq-h">Numerologist.com FAQs</h2>
      {faqs.map((f) => (<details><summary>{f.q}</summary><p>{f.a}</p></details>))}
    </section>

    <section class="related">
      <h2>Related Reading</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><a href="/best/numerology-reading/">Best Numerology Readings Compared</a></li>
        <li><a href="/numerology/">Numerology: The Complete Guide</a></li>
        <li><a href="/methodology/">How Our Readings Are Constructed</a></li>
      </ul>
    </section>
  </div>
</Base>
